  {
   "id": "n25",
   "type": "Note",
   "params": {
    "text": "HOW A BEZIER IS ACTUALLY BUILT.\n\nNot with a polynomial: with INTERPOLATION, repeated until only one point is left. That is de Casteljau's algorithm, and every CAD kernel \u2014 this one included \u2014 runs it under the hood.\n\nGREY: the control polygon, the 4 points joined up. VIOLET: walk a fraction t along each of its 3 sides, and join the 3 points you land on. GREEN: do it again on those, and you get 2 points, and one segment. RED: do it one last time, and the single point left IS a point of the curve.\n\nTRY THIS\n1. Drag `t` from 0 to 1: the ladder collapses and the red point sweeps out the whole curve. That yellow trail is the Bezier \u2014 and the blue curve behind it, drawn by the catalog's Bezier node, lies exactly on top of it. Same curve.\n2. DRAG A CONTROL POINT in the viewport (they carry gizmos). Notice the curve never goes THROUGH the middle two points: it is pulled towards them, and lets go. Only the first and last are actually touched.\n3. Put the two middle points on top of each other: the curve snaps taut.\n4. At t = 0 the point sits on P0; at t = 1 on P3. Nothing in between is promised \u2014 which is precisely what makes the curve smooth and controllable."
   },
   "position": [
